Process called "netbsd_x64_SYS_OBREAK" returns Integer:
    Return 17
End Process

@Reasoning
NetBSD syscall 17 is documented as `obreak` in sys/sys/syscall.h
(historical BSD naming preserved for ABI stability). The cross-platform
dispatcher's bare-name surface uses the POSIX-canonical name
`SYS_BRK`, which on NetBSD maps to the same syscall number (17). The
NetBSD `obreak(2)` interface adjusts the program break (data-segment
top) identically to Linux `brk(2)` semantics — passing 0 returns the
current break; passing a non-zero address requests a new break. The
name "obreak" reflects the "original break" terminology; modern NetBSD
userland uses `brk(3)` which wraps this syscall. Adding `SYS_BRK` as
a sibling bare-name preserves the cross-platform dispatcher contract
without renaming the existing `SYS_OBREAK` entry.
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h: SYS_obreak = 17; NetBSD
sys/uvm/uvm_mmap.c sys_obreak(); NetBSD libc brk(3).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process returning integer literal 17. The dispatcher routes
`SYS_BRK from NetBSDX64` to this proc on netbsd_x64 targets. The
high-level wrapper `netbsd_x64_syscall_brk(addr)` issues `netbsd_x64_syscall_1(17, addr)`,
trapping into NetBSD's `sys_obreak()` which adjusts the user-space
data segment. Returns the new break address in RAX on success, or
-errno on failure (typically -ENOMEM when the requested break exceeds
the soft RLIMIT_DATA limit).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant-return accessor; inlined. The underlying `obreak` syscall is
moderately expensive when it actually grows the data segment because
NetBSD must page-fault map fresh anonymous pages; querying the current
break (addr=0) is cheap. Allocators that issue `brk` frequently should
batch growth into larger chunks (typically 64 KiB or more) to amortise
the per-call overhead. Callers should prefer `mmap` with MAP_ANON for
allocations larger than a few pages — modern NetBSD malloc(3) does
exactly this and reserves `brk` for compatibility.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The `obreak` syscall enforces the RLIMIT_DATA resource limit; an
unprivileged caller cannot extend the data segment beyond the
soft-limit ceiling. The kernel zeros newly-mapped pages before exposing
them to user space, so there is no information leak from previous
allocations. Callers MUST NOT use `obreak` to reserve memory for
security-sensitive purposes that require non-swappable pages — those
must use `mlock(2)` after the allocation. Stack/heap collision is
prevented by the kernel's address-space layout; the syscall returns
-ENOMEM rather than corrupting the stack.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_x64_SYS_BRK" returns Integer:
    Return 17
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_SYS_GETFSSTAT" returns Integer:
    Return 18
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_SYS_GETPID_WITH_PPID" returns Integer:
    Return 20
End Process

@Reasoning
NetBSD syscall 20 is `getpid` per sys/sys/syscall.h. The NetBSD entry
point returns both the calling process's PID (in RAX) and the parent
PID (in RDX) on x86-64, which is why the platform's traditional alias
`SYS_GETPID_WITH_PPID` exists. The cross-platform dispatcher exposes
the POSIX-canonical bare-name `SYS_GETPID` which expects a single
integer return; both names share the same syscall number (20) because
the dual-return is a register-level convention, not a separate syscall.
Adding SYS_GETPID as a distinct bare-name proc lets the dispatcher
resolve the canonical name without rewiring the existing
`SYS_GETPID_WITH_PPID` callers.
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h: SYS_getpid = 20.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process returning integer literal 20. Used by the cross-platform
dispatcher to forward `SYS_GETPID` calls to NetBSD's syscall 20. The
caller's high-level wrapper (`getpid`) issues `netbsd_x64_syscall_0(20)` which
traps with RAX=20; the kernel returns the PID in RAX. Callers that
also need the PPID should continue using `SYS_GETPID_WITH_PPID` and
read RDX after the trap.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant-return accessor; compiler-inlined at every call site. The
underlying `getpid` syscall on NetBSD is one of the cheapest syscalls
(no kernel I/O, just a copy from `curlwp->l_proc->p_pid` to RAX). For
PID-stable workflows that read the PID once at process start and reuse
the cached value, prefer a single call at startup over repeated lookups;
modern NetBSD kernels (>= 6.0) cache the PID in libc's vDSO-equivalent
fast path, but Runa's direct-syscall wrapper does not exploit that.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
PID disclosure has low security impact under standard Unix policy:
PIDs are non-secret and visible via `ps`, `/proc/<pid>` (where mounted),
and `proc_info(2)` to any user. However, in sandboxed contexts (chroot
with pid_namespace, jail with `security.jail.see_other_pids=0`), the
returned PID is the in-namespace PID, not the host-global PID. Callers
constructing inter-process IPC keys from the PID must NOT assume PID
uniqueness across namespace boundaries.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_x64_SYS_GETPID" returns Integer:
    Return 20
End Process

