Process called "netbsd_x64_SYS_SETUID" returns Integer:
    Return 23
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_SYS_GETUID_WITH_EUID" returns Integer:
    Return 24
End Process

@Reasoning
NetBSD syscall 24 is `getuid` per sys/sys/syscall.h. As with `getpid`,
NetBSD's `getuid(2)` returns both the real UID (in RAX) and the
effective UID (in RDX) on x86-64; the platform's traditional alias
`SYS_GETUID_WITH_EUID` exposes the dual-return shape. The cross-platform
dispatcher expects the POSIX-canonical bare-name `SYS_GETUID` which
yields the real UID alone. Both names resolve to syscall 24; the dual
returns are register-level, not syscall-level.
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h: SYS_getuid = 24; NetBSD
sys/kern/kern_prot.c sys_getuid().
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process returning integer literal 24. The dispatcher forwards
`SYS_GETUID` to this proc on netbsd_x64 targets. The caller's high-level
`getuid` wrapper invokes `netbsd_x64_syscall_0(24)` and treats RAX as the real UID,
discarding RDX. Callers needing both real and effective UIDs in one
trap should use `SYS_GETUID_WITH_EUID` and read both RAX and RDX.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant-return accessor; compiler-inlined at the call site. The NetBSD
`getuid` syscall is among the cheapest on the system — kernel reads
`curlwp->l_cred->cr_uid` into RAX and returns. No I/O, no locks beyond
LWP credential ref. Repeated UID lookups within the same execution
context can be cached at the caller; UIDs do not change without a
deliberate `setuid` syscall.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
UID disclosure is non-sensitive under standard Unix policy. The
returned value is the calling process's real UID (the credential
established at process creation, NOT the effective UID used for
permission checks). Callers performing privilege checks MUST use the
effective UID (`SYS_GETEUID`, syscall 25); using the real UID for
authorisation decisions creates a setuid-binary confused-deputy
vulnerability: a process started by an unprivileged user but exec'd
from a setuid-root binary then incorrectly authorises itself as the
original unprivileged user.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_x64_SYS_GETUID" returns Integer:
    Return 24
End Process

