Process called "netbsd_x64_SYS_GETGID_WITH_EGID" returns Integer:
    Return 47
End Process

@Reasoning
NetBSD syscall 47 is `getgid` per sys/sys/syscall.h. NetBSD's
`getgid(2)` on x86-64 returns both the real GID (in RAX) and the
effective GID (in RDX) using the dual-return register convention, which
the platform exposes as `SYS_GETGID_WITH_EGID`. The cross-platform
dispatcher uses the POSIX-canonical bare-name `SYS_GETGID`; both
resolve to the same syscall number (47).
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h: SYS_getgid = 47; NetBSD
sys/kern/kern_prot.c sys_getgid().
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process returning integer literal 47. Dispatcher routes
`SYS_GETGID from NetBSDX64` here. The high-level `getgid` wrapper
issues `netbsd_x64_syscall_0(47)` and treats RAX as the real GID. Callers needing
both real and effective GIDs in a single trap should use
`SYS_GETGID_WITH_EGID` and read both RAX and RDX after the syscall
instruction completes.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant-return accessor; compiler-inlined. The underlying syscall
reads `curlwp->l_cred->cr_gid` into RAX with no locks or I/O; it is
among the cheapest NetBSD syscalls. Cache the result at process start
if the caller will read the GID more than once and the process does
not perform `setgid`/`setregid`.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
GID disclosure is non-sensitive. The returned value is the real GID,
not the effective GID. Authorisation decisions (file access checks,
group membership tests) MUST use the effective GID (`SYS_GETEGID`,
syscall 43) and the supplementary group set (`SYS_GETGROUPS`,
syscall 79). Using the real GID for access control on a setgid binary
yields confused-deputy behaviour analogous to the setuid case
documented under `SYS_GETUID`.
@End Security_Scope
