Note:
============================================================================
MEMORY MAPPING FLAGS
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "netbsd_x64_MAP_SHARED" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Share changes
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_MAP_PRIVATE" returns Integer:
    Return 2  Note: Changes are private
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_MAP_FIXED" returns Integer:
    Return 16  Note: Interpret addr exactly
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_MAP_ANON" returns Integer:
    Return 4096  Note: Anonymous memory (not file-backed)
End Process

@Reasoning
NetBSD's mmap flag for anonymous memory is `MAP_ANON` (value 0x1000 =
4096), defined in sys/sys/mman.h. The Linux-canonical name is
`MAP_ANONYMOUS`; NetBSD provides both names in user headers as
synonyms (MAP_ANONYMOUS is `#define`'d to MAP_ANON in
/usr/include/sys/mman.h on every NetBSD release since 5.0). The
cross-platform dispatcher's bare-name API uses `MAP_ANONYMOUS` (matching
Linux convention), so the NetBSD platform module must export that
name with the platform-correct value (0x1000), not the Linux value
(0x20). Returning 4096 here mirrors the value of `MAP_ANON` and is
the platform-correct flag for NetBSD's `mmap(2)`.
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/mman.h: MAP_ANON = 0x1000, MAP_ANONYMOUS aliased
to MAP_ANON; NetBSD sys/uvm/uvm_mmap.c sys_mmap() flag handling.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process returning integer literal 4096 (= 0x1000). The
dispatcher's `MAP_ANONYMOUS from NetBSDX64` lookup resolves here on
netbsd_x64 targets. Callers OR this value into the `flags` argument
of `syscall_mmap` to request anonymous (non-file-backed, zero-filled)
memory; the kernel ignores the `fd` argument when this flag is set and
backs the mapping with anonymous pages from the VM swap pool. The
mapping is removed by `munmap` or process exit.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant-return accessor; inlined. The runtime cost of using
MAP_ANONYMOUS is paid in the `mmap` syscall itself, not this accessor.
NetBSD's `uvm_mmap` defers page allocation until first-touch (lazy
zero-fill via fault handler), so reserving a large MAP_ANONYMOUS region
is cheap; the cost amortises across actual page touches. For
performance-sensitive allocators, prefer batching large allocations
over many small ones to reduce syscall and metadata overhead.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Anonymous memory pages are zero-filled by the kernel before exposure
to user space, eliminating the information-leak risk that exists with
uninitialised heap reuse. The mapping inherits the calling process's
address space permissions; MAP_ANONYMOUS|MAP_SHARED creates a region
shared with `fork`'d children but NOT with unrelated processes
(unlike POSIX shm). For inter-process anonymous shared memory, use
`shm_open` + mmap. Callers requesting executable anonymous mappings
(PROT_EXEC | MAP_ANONYMOUS) MUST be aware that NetBSD's PaX/MPROTECT
policy may reject the combination on hardened kernels; check the
runtime `security.pax.mprotect` sysctl before relying on W^X-violating
allocations.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_x64_MAP_ANONYMOUS" returns Integer:
    Return 4096  Note: NetBSD synonym for MAP_ANON (sys/mman.h alias)
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_MAP_STACK" returns Integer:
    Return 8192  Note: Region grows down (stack)
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_MAP_FILE" returns Integer:
    Return 0  Note: File mapping (default)
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
FILE PERMISSION MODE CONSTANTS
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
File mode constants exposed by the cross-platform dispatcher's bare-name
API. NetBSD inherits the BSD/POSIX `mode_t` encoding: the low 9 bits are
the rwxrwxrwx permission triplet, encoded octally as 0644 (rw-r--r--)
and 0755 (rwxr-xr-x). The accessor returns the decimal equivalent of
those octal constants, as required by the syscall ABI which treats the
`mode` argument as a plain integer with no octal interpretation at the
kernel boundary. NetBSD's permission semantics for these constants are
identical to Linux/FreeBSD/Darwin because they originate in the POSIX
`<sys/stat.h>` specification and are stable across all Unix variants.
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/stat.h (S_IRUSR=0400, S_IWUSR=0200, S_IRGRP=0040,
S_IWGRP=0020, S_IROTH=0004, S_IWOTH=0002, S_IXUSR=0100, S_IXGRP=0010,
S_IXOTH=0001). 0644 = 0400 | 0200 | 0040 | 0004 = 420 decimal.
0755 = 0400 | 0200 | 0100 | 0040 | 0010 | 0004 | 0001 = 493 decimal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each accessor is a nullary Process returning the constant integer
value. The dispatcher's `MODE_0644 from NetBSDX64` (and respectively
`MODE_0755`) lookup resolves here on netbsd_x64 targets via the
bare-name route. Callers OR these values into the `mode` argument of
`creat`, `open(O_CREAT)`, `mkdir`, and `chmod` to request the
corresponding permission triplet. The values are passed verbatim
through to NetBSD's `sys_chmod` / `sys_mkdir` / `sys_open` which apply
the kernel's umask before recording the final mode in the inode.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler inlines at every call site, leaving zero
call overhead. Do not introduce any runtime computation here. The
overall cost of a file-creation operation is dominated by the
filesystem write, not by mode evaluation; these accessors are not on
any hot path that could measurably improve from further optimisation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a file-permission constant carries no security state. Callers
who use the returned value as a `mode` argument are responsible for
ensuring the requested permission matches the intended access policy.
World-readable (0644) is appropriate for non-sensitive files; group-and-
world-executable (0755) is appropriate for binaries and directories.
Files holding secrets (private keys, credentials, session tokens) MUST
use 0600 or 0400 — neither value is exposed via this accessor; callers
must construct those modes inline. NetBSD's default umask (0022) will
strip world-write from 0644 / 0755 even if a caller mistakenly ORs in
S_IWOTH; nevertheless, callers should not rely on umask to enforce
security boundaries.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_x64_MODE_0644" returns Integer:
    Return 420  Note: 0644 octal = rw-r--r--
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_MODE_0755" returns Integer:
    Return 493  Note: 0755 octal = rwxr-xr-x
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
FILE SEEK WHENCE CONSTANTS
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
The `whence` argument to `lseek(2)` selects how the supplied offset is
interpreted: SEEK_SET (0) measures from the start of the file,
SEEK_CUR (1) measures relative to the current file position, SEEK_END
(2) measures relative to end-of-file. NetBSD inherits the POSIX-mandated
values from sys/sys/unistd.h (which is included by sys/fcntl.h) and
they are stable across every Unix variant. The cross-platform
dispatcher's bare-name API exposes these constants so the
`syscall_lseek` wrapper's `whence` parameter resolves to the correct
value on every platform.
Source: NetBSD sys/sys/unistd.h: SEEK_SET = 0, SEEK_CUR = 1,
SEEK_END = 2; POSIX-1.2008 `<unistd.h>`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process accessors returning the constant integer values. The
dispatcher routes `SEEK_SET from NetBSDX64` (and respectively
`SEEK_CUR`, `SEEK_END`) to these procs on netbsd_x64 targets. Callers
pass the accessor's return value as the third argument to
`netbsd_x64_syscall_lseek(fd, offset, whence)`. Bodies are non-side-effecting
and trivially inlinable.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined at every call site. No runtime
cost. Do not wrap these in any additional indirection; the dispatcher
already selects the platform-correct value at the dispatch boundary.
The `lseek` syscall itself is moderately cheap on local filesystems
(updates only the in-kernel file-table offset) but expensive on
network filesystems with mandatory positional locking.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a seek-whence constant has no security implications on its
own. Callers that pass user-influenced `offset` values into `lseek`
with these whence flags MUST validate the resulting absolute file
position against the file's permitted range; an attacker-controlled
negative offset combined with SEEK_END can yield an unexpected
position prior to file start, which NetBSD's `sys_lseek` will reject
with EINVAL on conforming kernels but a buggy caller might still
trust the returned offset and corrupt downstream computations.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_x64_SEEK_SET" returns Integer:
    Return 0  Note: Seek from beginning of file
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_SEEK_CUR" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Seek from current position
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_SEEK_END" returns Integer:
    Return 2  Note: Seek from end of file
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
GENERIC SYSCALL WRAPPERS
============================================================================
:End Note

Note:
NetBSD x86-64 syscall convention:
- RAX = syscall number
- RDI, RSI, RDX, R10, R8, R9 = arguments 1-6
- Stack = arguments 7+
- Return value in RAX
:End Note

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_0" takes syscall_number as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: NetBSD x86-64 syscall with 0 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into RAX
        mov rax, [rbp-8]

        # Execute syscall
        syscall

        # Store result from RAX
        mov [rbp-16], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_1" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: NetBSD x86-64 syscall with 1 argument
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into RAX
        mov rax, [rbp-8]

        # Load argument 1 into RDI
        mov rdi, [rbp-16]

        # Execute syscall
        syscall

        # Store result from RAX
        mov [rbp-24], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_2" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: NetBSD x86-64 syscall with 2 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into RAX
        mov rax, [rbp-8]

        # Load arguments 1-2 into RDI, RSI
        mov rdi, [rbp-16]
        mov rsi, [rbp-24]

        # Execute syscall
        syscall

        # Store result from RAX
        mov [rbp-32], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_3" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: NetBSD x86-64 syscall with 3 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into RAX
        mov rax, [rbp-8]

        # Load arguments 1-3 into RDI, RSI, RDX
        mov rdi, [rbp-16]
        mov rsi, [rbp-24]
        mov rdx, [rbp-32]

        # Execute syscall
        syscall

        # Store result from RAX
        mov [rbp-40], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_4" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: NetBSD x86-64 syscall with 4 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into RAX
        mov rax, [rbp-8]

        # Load arguments 1-4 into RDI, RSI, RDX, R10
        mov rdi, [rbp-16]
        mov rsi, [rbp-24]
        mov rdx, [rbp-32]
        mov r10, [rbp-40]

        # Execute syscall
        syscall

        # Store result from RAX
        mov [rbp-48], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_5" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer, arg5 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: NetBSD x86-64 syscall with 5 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into RAX
        mov rax, [rbp-8]

        # Load arguments 1-5 into RDI, RSI, RDX, R10, R8
        mov rdi, [rbp-16]
        mov rsi, [rbp-24]
        mov rdx, [rbp-32]
        mov r10, [rbp-40]
        mov r8, [rbp-48]

        # Execute syscall
        syscall

        # Store result from RAX
        mov [rbp-56], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_6" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer, arg5 as Integer, arg6 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: NetBSD x86-64 syscall with 6 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into RAX
        mov rax, [rbp-8]

        # Load arguments 1-6 into RDI, RSI, RDX, R10, R8, R9
        mov rdi, [rbp-16]
        mov rsi, [rbp-24]
        mov rdx, [rbp-32]
        mov r10, [rbp-40]
        mov r8, [rbp-48]
        mov r9, [rbp-56]

        # Execute syscall
        syscall

        # Store result from RAX
        mov [rbp-64], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
DISPATCHER-CONTRACT SYSCALL_X WRAPPERS
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
The cross-platform syscall dispatcher exposes 10 `syscall_<name>` bare-
name procs (syscall_read, syscall_write, syscall_open, syscall_close,
syscall_exit, syscall_brk, syscall_mmap, syscall_munmap, syscall_fstat,
syscall_lseek). Each platform module must export these names so the
dispatcher's bare-name routing resolves uniformly across platforms.
On NetBSD x86-64, each wrapper routes through the matching `syscall_N`
generic dispatcher with the NetBSD-correct SYS_* number from
sys/sys/syscall.h: read=3, write=4, open=5, close=6, exit=1, brk=17
(SYS_obreak), mmap=197, munmap=73, fstat=440, lseek=199.

These are NOT duplicates of the lower-section `read`/`write`/`open`/...
POSIX-named wrappers below: those use POSIX-canonical short names for
compatibility with the v0.0.7.5-era Runa standard library; the
`syscall_<name>` forms are what the platform-dispatch infrastructure
expects per the P2-B design's "Per-platform syscall inventory" section
(66-proc surface).

Source for syscall numbers: NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h (kern_syscalls.master
generated). Numbers stable since NetBSD 9.0; some (mmap=197, fstat=440,
lseek=199) reflect post-time_t-64 ABI versions and differ from the
historical compat-32 versions present elsewhere in this file.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each wrapper computes the syscall number via the matching SYS_*
accessor (itself a constant return on netbsd_x64) and forwards the
arguments to the `syscall_N` generic dispatcher matching the arity.
The generic dispatcher loads RAX with the syscall number and RDI/RSI/
RDX/R10/R8/R9 with arguments per the System V AMD64 ABI, then issues
the `syscall` instruction. Negative RAX values are NetBSD-ABI errno
indications which the wrapper propagates unchanged to the caller.

Argument-passing convention (per-wrapper):
- netbsd_x64_syscall_read(fd, buf, count) -> netbsd_x64_SYS_READ(3) via syscall_3
- netbsd_x64_syscall_write(fd, buf, count) -> netbsd_x64_SYS_WRITE(4) via syscall_3
- netbsd_x64_syscall_open(path, flags, mode) -> netbsd_x64_SYS_OPEN(5) via syscall_3
- netbsd_x64_syscall_close(fd) -> netbsd_x64_SYS_CLOSE(6) via syscall_1
- netbsd_x64_syscall_exit(status) -> netbsd_x64_SYS_EXIT(1) via syscall_1 (does not return)
- netbsd_x64_syscall_brk(addr) -> netbsd_x64_SYS_BRK(17 = SYS_obreak) via syscall_1
- netbsd_x64_syscall_mmap(addr, len, prot, flags, fd, offset) -> netbsd_x64_SYS_MMAP(197) via syscall_6
- netbsd_x64_syscall_munmap(addr, len) -> netbsd_x64_SYS_MUNMAP(73) via syscall_2
- netbsd_x64_syscall_fstat(fd, statbuf) -> netbsd_x64_SYS_FSTAT(440) via syscall_2 (modern stat_t)
- netbsd_x64_syscall_lseek(fd, offset, whence) -> netbsd_x64_SYS_LSEEK(199) via syscall_3

Note on mmap: NetBSD's `mmap(2)` takes a 64-bit offset directly (no
mmap2/offset-shifted variant) because NetBSD x86-64 has been LP64 since
inception. The `syscall_mmap` wrapper passes `offset` verbatim.

Note on fstat: SYS_FSTAT = 440 corresponds to the modern `stat_t`
layout (NetBSD >= 5.0, ino_t = 64-bit, time_t = 64-bit). Earlier
syscall numbers (62, 189, 279, 388) refer to historical stat layouts
preserved for backward compatibility; the dispatcher's `syscall_fstat`
contract expects the modern layout, so the wrapper routes to 440.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Each wrapper compiles down to: load constant syscall number into RAX,
marshal arguments through the stack frame to RDI/RSI/RDX/R10/R8/R9,
issue `syscall`. Total cost is dominated by the kernel-mode trap, not
the wrapper's Runa-level indirection. The wrapper itself adds 2-3
instructions of glue beyond the generic syscall_N body.

For hot-path syscall sites (e.g. read/write in tight I/O loops), prefer
calling the generic `syscall_3` directly with the SYS_* constant
inlined, avoiding the intermediate wrapper. The wrapper exists for
dispatcher-contract compliance, not as a recommended fast-path entry.

NetBSD x86-64 uses the `syscall` instruction (vs `int 0x80`), which
on modern CPUs (post-Nehalem) is faster than the legacy interrupt
path; no further micro-optimisation is possible at the wrapper level.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
File-descriptor and pointer arguments are passed verbatim to the
kernel. The wrapper performs no validation; the NetBSD kernel enforces
all access controls (UID/GID checks, `securelevel`, `veriexec` if
configured, MAC framework policy if loaded). Callers must NOT use
these wrappers to issue syscalls on behalf of an untrusted source
without prior privilege separation.

In particular:
- syscall_open: untrusted `path` strings can traverse the filesystem
  subject only to DAC and chroot policy; sandboxed callers must
  impose a chroot or use NetBSD's `kauth(9)` listener framework
  before invoking.
- syscall_mmap with PROT_EXEC: writable+executable mappings violate
  W^X; NetBSD's PaX/MPROTECT policy rejects the combination on
  hardened kernels (`security.pax.mprotect.global=1`). Callers should
  request PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE then `mprotect` up to PROT_EXEC after
  content is written.
- syscall_exit: terminates the entire process (all LWPs) on NetBSD
  because NetBSD does not distinguish exit from exit_group at the
  syscall level (see SYS_EXIT_GROUP @Reasoning above).
- syscall_brk: enforces RLIMIT_DATA; unprivileged callers cannot
  bypass the soft limit.

Errno propagation: kernel returns -errno in RAX for failure. The
wrapper returns this verbatim; positive values are syscall results
(byte counts, file descriptors, addresses, file offsets). Caller MUST
check sign of return value before treating it as a syscall result.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_read" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read from file descriptor; routes through SYS_READ (3) on netbsd_x64
    Let syscall_num be netbsd_x64_SYS_READ()
    Return netbsd_x64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_write" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Write to file descriptor; routes through SYS_WRITE (4) on netbsd_x64
    Let syscall_num be netbsd_x64_SYS_WRITE()
    Return netbsd_x64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_open" takes filename as Integer, flags as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Open file; routes through SYS_OPEN (5) on netbsd_x64
    Let syscall_num be netbsd_x64_SYS_OPEN()
    Return netbsd_x64_syscall_3(syscall_num, filename, flags, mode)
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_close" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Close file descriptor; routes through SYS_CLOSE (6) on netbsd_x64
    Let syscall_num be netbsd_x64_SYS_CLOSE()
    Return netbsd_x64_syscall_1(syscall_num, fd)
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_exit" takes status as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Terminate calling process; routes through SYS_EXIT (1) on netbsd_x64
    Does not return on success; the Return statement is unreachable
    but required to satisfy the dispatcher's Integer-return contract
    :End Note
    Let syscall_num be netbsd_x64_SYS_EXIT()
    Return netbsd_x64_syscall_1(syscall_num, status)
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_brk" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Adjust program break; routes through SYS_BRK (17 = SYS_obreak) on netbsd_x64
    addr=0 queries current break; non-zero requests new break address
    :End Note
    Let syscall_num be netbsd_x64_SYS_BRK()
    Return netbsd_x64_syscall_1(syscall_num, addr)
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_mmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer, prot as Integer, flags as Integer, fd as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Map memory; routes through SYS_MMAP (197) on netbsd_x64
    NetBSD x86-64 mmap takes 64-bit offset directly (no mmap2 entry)
    :End Note
    Let syscall_num be netbsd_x64_SYS_MMAP()
    Return netbsd_x64_syscall_6(syscall_num, addr, length, prot, flags, fd, offset)
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_munmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unmap memory; routes through SYS_MUNMAP (73) on netbsd_x64
    Let syscall_num be netbsd_x64_SYS_MUNMAP()
    Return netbsd_x64_syscall_2(syscall_num, addr, length)
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_fstat" takes fd as Integer, statbuf as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Get file status by fd; routes through SYS_FSTAT (440) on netbsd_x64
    440 is the modern stat_t layout (NetBSD >= 5.0); historical entries
    (62, 189, 279, 388) refer to obsolete compat layouts
    :End Note
    Let syscall_num be netbsd_x64_SYS_FSTAT()
    Return netbsd_x64_syscall_2(syscall_num, fd, statbuf)
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_lseek" takes fd as Integer, offset as Integer, whence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Reposition file offset; routes through SYS_LSEEK (199) on netbsd_x64
    Let syscall_num be netbsd_x64_SYS_LSEEK()
    Return netbsd_x64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, offset, whence)
End Process

Process called "netbsd_x64_syscall_ioctl" takes fd as Integer, cmd as Integer, arg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX ioctl(2) on NetBSD amd64.
    SYS_ioctl is 54 (NetBSD sys/sys/syscall.h, inherited from the
    historical 4.4BSD numbering and frozen since). Three-arg shape
    (fd, request, argp). NetBSD amd64 uses the standard System V
    AMD64 ABI (rdi, rsi, rdx) and the syscall instruction.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Composes the syscall by calling netbsd_x64_SYS_IOCTL() (returns
    54) and netbsd_x64_syscall_3(54, fd, cmd, arg). NetBSD's syscall
    convention loads 54 into rax, fd into rdi, cmd into rsi, arg into
    rdx, then issues syscall; rax holds the result with the carry
    flag set on error (converted to -errno inside syscall_3).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) dispatch in the NetBSD kernel — one fd-table lookup and a
    driver vtable jump. NetBSD's vfs_ioctl path is straightforward;
    the overhead is dominated by the kernel-entry transition itself.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The NetBSD kernel validates fd against the per-process file
    descriptor table and dispatches cmd through fileops.fo_ioctl.
    arg, if a pointer, is dereferenced by the kernel with the
    structure size implied by cmd; callers must size the buffer to
    match. NetBSD's kauth secmodel may intercept ioctl(2) for
    processes operating under restricted credentials.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let syscall_num be netbsd_x64_SYS_IOCTL()
    Return netbsd_x64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, cmd, arg)
End Process

